The studios don’t get 100% of the money from you buying a ticket at a cinema. If that’s how it worked cinemas wouldn’t be able to make enough money to survive.

The average rate is 50%

>person buys ticket to see movie
>half that money goes to the local cinema (and the company which owns a a bunch of that brand of cinema)
>half goes to the studio the movie they are showing produced

Even with this, cinemas make most of their profit from food and drink bought there.

Sometimes if the movie is highly anticipated and will bring huge crowds. The split is different. Star Wars sequel movies got special deals for example because the cinemas had a guaranteed massive turnout, so they were cool with Disney getting 60%.

At an assembly at Los Alamos on August 6 (the evening of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima), Oppenheimer took to the stage and clasped his hands together "like a prize-winning boxer" while the crowd cheered. He noted his regret the weapon had not been available in time to use against Nazi Germany.[122] But he and many of the project staff were very upset about the bombing of Nagasaki, as they did not feel the second bomb was necessary from a military point of view.[123] He traveled to Washington on August 17 to hand-deliver a letter to Secretary of War Henry L. Stimson expressing his revulsion and his wish to see nuclear weapons banned.[124] In October 1945, Oppenheimer was granted an interview with President Harry S. Truman. The meeting went badly after Oppenheimer said he felt he had "blood on my hands". The remark infuriated Truman and put an end to the meeting. Truman later told his Undersecretary of State Dean Acheson, "I don't want to see that son-of-a-bitch in this office ever again."[125]

I'm going to assume you are looking for in-universe reasons as the "real" reasons are pretty obvious.
>Xindi
There aren't that many of them, they are scattered all over, and the thing that unified their people (the Guardians guiding them against the threat they apparently faced) ended up being a lie. Presumedly they spend a lot of time trying to get back together (recall that they had a rather violent falling out the amongst themselves the last we saw, civil war might have been possible) and then figure out what to work towards (a new homeworld?). We know by the time of the Guardians return and invasion in the 2500s that the Xindi have joined the federation and are serving in SF. So prior to that we can assume they are outside Fed space getting their shit together.
>all sorts of other ENT races
What sorts of other races did you have in mind?
>Why do Andorians dissapear after TOS?
They don't. We only see them a few times in TNG sure, but we see them often enough in the background of DS( (a remote installation far from Andoria), STD, PIC, LD, and I think there might have even been one in SNW. Additionally, in PRO there is a major side character who is Andorian who shows up a fair bit in the second half of the season. Why aren't there more? They are short lived and seem to not have many children so may be a relatively small proportion of the Federation by later series. Additionally, they seem a little xenophobic so may be less inclined to join Starfleet, especially on missions/ships that push the borders.

I think there is a kind of mystique about the time period immediately prior to your own birth. As a kid you grow up around the debris of it, you have memories from being very young of rooms and clothing that still retain aesthetics from before your birth, your parents were not parents and thus normal people but whatever they were up to eventually resulted in you. It is the fact that something can be so close, vaguely familiar, but also beyond your grasp. There is a mystique to that.
